nRH agonists?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initial hormone surge followed by suppression","Direct inhibition of testicular testosterone synthesis","Competitive antagonism of pituitary GnRH receptors","Initial hormone suppression followed by rebound surge","Irreversible destruction of pituitary gonadotrophs"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe therapeutic mechanism of GnRH agonists involves an \u003Cstrong\u003Einitial hormone surge followed by suppression\u003C/strong\u003E. When first administered, these drugs stimulate pituitary GnRH receptors, causing a temporary increase in luteinising hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) release. However, continuous exposure leads to receptor downregulation and desensitisation, ultimately suppressing hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of testicular testosterone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - The effect on testosterone is indirect via suppression of LH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive antagonism of pituitary GnRH receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - GnRH agonists activate rather than block receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial hormone suppression followed by rebound surge\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of what occurs with GnRH agonists\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrreversible destruction of pituitary gonadotrophs\u003C/strong\u003E - The effect is reversible and does not involve cell destruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism explains why patients may experience temporary worsening of symptoms (tumour flare) when starting GnRH agonist therapy, necessitating concurrent anti-androgen treatment during initiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH) agonists initially cause a surge in luteinising hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone before leading to receptor downregulation.","Continuous GnRH agonist exposure leads to decreased gonadotrophin release through desensitisation of pituitary receptors.","GnRH agonists are used clinically to suppress testosterone production in prostate cancer treatment."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61724"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61724"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:23:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:26:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9334"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"